description.narrative: By end 2021, the government and partners, including communities and children themselves, have the human and material resources and infrastructure to offer (1) operational and accessible birth registration services with reliable statistics (2) a justice system that is responsive to the specific needs of children, and (3) community protection mechanisms against child marriage, which contributes to Birth Registration, Child Protection Systems, Child Protection â€“ General, Child Protection â€“ Strengthen Families And Communities, Data And Child Protection, Justice For Children, Prevention Of Harmful Practice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 6: By the end of 2022, women, children and adolescents, especially the most vulnerable, make greater use of quality public protection services (civil registration service, juvenile justice and social assistance).

description.narrative: In 2021, UNICEF placed a strong emphasis on supporting the implementation of the legal and institutional reform of the civil registration system and vital statistics systems. It has contributed to strengthening coordination between civil registration and health services to gradually improve the registration of children’s birth within the legal timeframe; 185,343 children, of whom 94,317 girls and 91,026 boys, in 14/23 provinces had their births registered and were issued with birth certificates, i.e. over 234% of the target set for 2021. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:02/02/2022
